suggestedFix:
In `read_secret`, use a secure string type (e.g., `zeroize::Zeroizing<String>`) so the buffer is zeroed on drop, or manually zero the buffer before returning an error in any confirmation/validation path. Concretely, change:
```rust
use zeroize::Zeroizing;

pub fn read_secret(prompt: &str) -> io::Result<Zeroizing<String>> {
    let mut password = Zeroizing::new(String::new());
    // ... rest of function unchanged ...
    Ok(password)
}
```
This ensures that if the returned secret is dropped (e.g., on a mismatch in a confirm-password flow), the backing memory is zeroed. Additionally, any caller that compares two passwords and discards the first on mismatch should explicitly call `zeroize()` on the discarded value before the function returns.
